g.title: n0
g.text: P1
The natural inclination here is to say
that these robots are feeling emotion.

g.title: n11
g.text: Physicalist response 1
Douglas Adams' Hitchhiker's Guide to
Galaxy has robot Marvin that feels
depressed. That's how he behaves and
that's why we ascribe depression to
him.

g.title: n13
g.text: Physicalist response 2
2001 Space Odyssey has a computer
called HAL that says that he is
afraid, as he is being switched off.
HAL is behaving the way you would
expect it to behave if it felt fear.

g.title: n1
g.text: Does a blind person really know what it
is like to see the color? Even if he
is scientifically taught that one
object is red and another is blue,
does he really experience what it is
like to see red?

g.title: n12
g.text: Dualist response 1
There is a behavioural aspect of
feeling emotions, and there is the
experience of it. No mere machine can
possibly have qualitative experience,
but humans have it. Humans are
therefore no merely physical objects.

g.title: n2
g.text: What about smell of a pineapple? Etc.
These things are called 'Qualia' -
qualitative aspects of things.

g.title: n3
g.text: This is why we should not be dismissive
of the dualist viewpoint. We don't
know enough about consciousness yet to
know whether or not it can be
explained in physical terms.

g.title: n14
g.text: Physicalist admission
Ideally we should say "Here's how to
build a machine that can be conscious
in this sense" ... But we don't know
how to explain it in Physicalist
terms.

g.title: n4
g.text: It is very important to remember that
we are not looking for just any
explanation, but for the best
explanation. How much of an
explanation is it to say that
consciousness is not based in the body
but in the soul? (physicalist)

g.title: n10
g.text: Dualist argument 1
No purely physical object could feel.
Humans can feel. Therefore humans are
not purely physical objects.

g.title: n5
g.text: When chess program Deep Fritz beat
Kramnik it was being creative

g.title: n16
g.text: Physicalist response 3
Machines can also be creative.

g.title: n6
g.text: Software came up with a new proof of
Pythagorean Theorem that nobody in the
world has come up with before. Without
being predjudiced why can't we say
that the machine is not being
creative?

g.title: n15
g.text: Dualist argument 2
People can be creative.

g.title: n17
g.text: Dualist response 2
Even if a program is being "creative"
it is just automatically following the
code. All the computer can do is
automatically follow the program. It
doesn't have free will. Humans have
free will.

g.title: n7
g.text: We have free will

g.title: n18
g.text: Dualist argument 4
We are not a purely physical system.

g.title: n8
g.text: Nothing subject to determinism has free
will

g.title: n9
g.text: All purely physical systems are subject
to determinism
